{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656888"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18776"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18776"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80318"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65587"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7594"},{"type":"tags","id":"7657"},{"type":"tags","id":"10096"},{"type":"tags","id":"10478"},{"type":"tags","id":"10482"},{"type":"tags","id":"10484"},{"type":"tags","id":"11376"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26637"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80318"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlandular secretion can occur through several distinct mechanisms. Understanding these mechanisms helps explain how different exocrine glands function in the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes merocrine secretion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Passive transport across plasma membrane","Disintegration of entire secretory cell","Detachment of cell apex during secretion","Transport of intact cells into duct","Exocytosis of secretory vesicles"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe defining characteristic of merocrine secretion is \u003Cstrong\u003Eexocytosis of secretory vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E. In this process, products are packaged within membrane-bound vesicles that fuse with the cell membrane to release their contents. This mechanism preserves cell integrity and allows sustained secretory function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive transport across plasma membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - Most secretory products are too large for simple diffusion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisintegration of entire secretory cell\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes holocrine secretion (e.g. sebaceous glands)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetachment of cell apex during secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes apocrine secretion (e.g. mammary glands)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of intact cells into duct\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a physiological secretory mechanism\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMerocrine secretion is found in most exocrine glands including the pancreas and salivary glands, representing the most efficient secretory mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Exocrine glands produce secretions that are released onto surfaces or into cavities via ducts.","Merocrine secretion involves exocytosis of vesicles while maintaining cellular integrity.","Merocrine secretion is the predominant mechanism in most exocrine glands including pancreas and salivary glands."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65587"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18776"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65587"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T13:02:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T13:03:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11508"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80318"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt"